## Part 2 — What to Change for DMs

Your current architecture sends messages to **channels within guilds**. DMs are private conversations between **two users**, independent of any guild. Here's what you need:

### Architecture Decision

You already have a `ChannelType` enum with `TEXT` and `ANNOUNCEMENT`. The cleanest approach: **add `DM` as a new channel type** and reuse your existing message infrastructure.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph Current
        Guild --> Channel["Channel (TEXT/ANNOUNCEMENT)"]
        Channel --> Message
    end
    subgraph New
        User1["User A"] --> DMChannel["Channel (type=DM, guild=null)"]
        User2["User B"] --> DMChannel
        DMChannel --> DMMessage["Message (same entity)"]
    end
```

### Backend Changes Needed

#### 1. Add `DM` to ChannelType enum

```diff
 // channel/model/ChannelType.java
 public enum ChannelType {
     TEXT,
-    ANNOUNCEMENT
+    ANNOUNCEMENT,
+    DM
 }
```

#### 2. Make `guild` nullable on ChannelEntity

DM channels don't belong to a guild:

```diff
 // channel/entity/ChannelEntity.java

- @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY, optional = false)
- @JoinColumn(name = "guild_id", nullable = false, updatable = false)
+ @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
+ @JoinColumn(name = "guild_id", updatable = false)
  private GuildEntity guild;
```

#### 3. Create a DM participants join table entity

```java
// channel/entity/DmParticipantEntity.java

@Entity
@Table(
    name = "dm_participants",
    uniqueConstraints = @UniqueConstraint(columnNames = {"channel_id", "user_id"})
)
@Getter @Setter @NoArgsConstructor @AllArgsConstructor @Builder
public class DmParticipantEntity {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.UUID)
    private UUID id;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "channel_id", nullable = false)
    private ChannelEntity channel;

    @ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id", nullable = false)
    private UserEntity user;
}
```

#### 4. Create DmRepository

```java
// channel/repository/DmParticipantRepository.java

public interface DmParticipantRepository extends JpaRepository<DmParticipantEntity, UUID> {

    // Find all DM channels for a user
    @Query("""
        SELECT dp.channel FROM DmParticipantEntity dp
        WHERE dp.user.id = :userId AND dp.channel.type = 'DM'
    """)
    List<ChannelEntity> findDmChannelsForUser(@Param("userId") UUID userId);

    // Find existing DM channel between two users
    @Query("""
        SELECT dp1.channel FROM DmParticipantEntity dp1
        JOIN DmParticipantEntity dp2 ON dp1.channel = dp2.channel
        WHERE dp1.user.id = :userA AND dp2.user.id = :userB
        AND dp1.channel.type = 'DM'
    """)
    Optional<ChannelEntity> findDmBetween(@Param("userA") UUID userA, @Param("userB") UUID userB);
}
```

#### 5. Create DmController

```java
// channel/controller/DmController.java

@RestController
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/dm")
@Tag(name = "Direct Messages", description = "APIs for DM conversations")
public class DmController {

    private final DmService dmService;

    /**
     * Open (or get existing) DM channel with another user.
     * POST /api/v1/dm/{targetUserId}
     */
    @PostMapping("/{targetUserId}")
    public ResponseEntity<ChannelResponse> openDm(
            @PathVariable UUID targetUserId,
            @AuthenticationPrincipal UserDetails principal
    ) {
        UUID currentUserId = UUID.fromString(principal.getUsername());
        return ResponseEntity.ok(dmService.getOrCreateDm(currentUserId, targetUserId));
    }

    /**
     * List all my DM conversations.
     * GET /api/v1/dm
     */
    @GetMapping
    public ResponseEntity<List<ChannelResponse>> getMyDms(
            @AuthenticationPrincipal UserDetails principal
    ) {
        UUID currentUserId = UUID.fromString(principal.getUsername());
        return ResponseEntity.ok(dmService.getDmsForUser(currentUserId));
    }
}
```

#### 6. Create DmService

```java
// channel/service/DmService.java

@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class DmService {

    private final ChannelRepository channelRepository;
    private final DmParticipantRepository dmParticipantRepository;

    @Transactional
    public ChannelResponse getOrCreateDm(UUID userA, UUID userB) {
        // Check if DM already exists
        return dmParticipantRepository.findDmBetween(userA, userB)
                .map(this::toResponse)
                .orElseGet(() -> createDm(userA, userB));
    }

    private ChannelResponse createDm(UUID userA, UUID userB) {
        ChannelEntity channel = ChannelEntity.builder()
                .name("DM")          // DMs don't need a visible name
                .type(ChannelType.DM)
                .guild(null)          // No guild
                .build();

        channel = channelRepository.save(channel);

        // Add both participants
        dmParticipantRepository.save(DmParticipantEntity.builder()
                .channel(channel).user(/* fetch userA entity */).build());
        dmParticipantRepository.save(DmParticipantEntity.builder()
                .channel(channel).user(/* fetch userB entity */).build());

        return toResponse(channel);
    }
}
```

#### 7. How DM messaging works (no new WebSocket code needed!)

Here's the beauty — **your existing `ChatController.sendMessage()` already works for DMs**. A DM channel is just a channel with `type=DM`. The flow is:

1. User A calls `POST /api/v1/dm/{userB_id}` → gets back a `channelId`
2. Both users subscribe to `/group/channel/{dmChannelId}`
3. Either user sends via `/app/chat/{dmChannelId}`
4. Both receive the broadcast on `/group/channel/{dmChannelId}`

> [!TIP]
> Your existing `@MessageMapping("/chat/{channelId}")` and `convertAndSend("/group/channel/" + channelId)` work identically for DMs. No new STOMP endpoints needed.

### React Side — DM Integration

```js
// Add to api.js

export async function openDm(targetUserId) {
  return request(`/dm/${targetUserId}`, { method: "POST" });
}

export async function getMyDms() {
  return request("/dm");
}
```

```jsx
// Using the DM — same ChatRoom component!

async function startDm(targetUserId) {
  const dmChannel = await openDm(targetUserId);
  // Navigate to ChatRoom with dmChannel.id
  // <ChatRoom channelId={dmChannel.id} />
}
```

The `ChatRoom` component and `useChat` hook work **exactly the same** for DMs — because a DM is just a channel.

